Sending Mail
\layout Subsection

To: CC: and BCC: Settings
\layout Standard

All of these fields accept either mail addresses, aliases or folder names.
 Aliases must be expanded by using the tabulator key or the Expand button
 next to the fields.
 If multiple entries match the text, you will be prompted with a list to
 choose from.
 
\layout Subsubsection

Using Folder names as an address
\layout Standard

Folder names can be entered by prefixing them with a hash ('#') sign.
 This will cause a copy of the message to be saved in the folder with this
 name.
 If no such folder exists, it will be created in the mail folder directory.
 For example, entering 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

joe.user@foo.com, #myMail
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 in the To: field, will send the mail to Joe User and save a copy of it
 in the folder 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

myMail
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

.
 Note, that if you have your folders organised hierarchically, you must
 specify the full path to the folder in the folder tree control.
 An example: If you have a group of folders in the tree, called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

Work
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 and want to save a copy of the message to the folder 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

TODO
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 which is a sub-folder of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

Work
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

, you need to add 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

#Work/TODO
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 in the address field.
 Instead of using the To: field for this, you can also use CC: or BCC:,
 there is no difference.
\layout Subsubsection

To:
\layout Standard

The primary address to which to send the message, multiple addresses can
 be entered and must be comma-separated.
\layout Subsubsection

CC:
\layout Standard

CC means Carbon Copy - copies of the message will get sent to the addresses
 listed here.
 
\layout Subsubsection

BCC:
\layout Standard

BCC means Blind Carbon Copy - like CC:, copies will be sent to the addresses
 listed here, but the addresses will not be stored in the mail header.
 This allows you to send copies without other recipients of the message
 knowing about it.
